-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Kenya Commercial Bank, United Bank for Africa
-- Sarah McGregor
-- 2010-07-13T16:32:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-13/sub-saharan-african-stocks-kenya-commercial-bank-united-bank-for-africa.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  gained for
a fifth day, rising 0.5 percent to 1,676.4 at the close in the
capital, Port Louis.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  snapped three days of gains,
falling 0.1 percent to 75.13 at the close in Nairobi. The
 Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  climbed 0.8 percent to
24,842.01, while Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  added 0.3
percent to 757.34. The  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index 
retreated 2.4 percent to 6,367.93.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 KenolKobil Ltd.  (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in seven African countries, climbed for a fifth day,
gaining 20 cents, or 1.9 percent, to 10.95 shillings. Oil
advanced the most in a month in New York, rising as much as 3.2
percent to $77.37 a barrel.  
 Kenya Commercial Bank Ltd.  (KNCB KN), the East African
nation’s biggest lender by branches, climbed 5 cents, or 0.3
percent, to 17.80 shillings, the highest since July 8. Net
income increased 21 percent to 2.9 billion shillings ($35.5
million) in the fiscal first half from a year earlier, Chief
Executive Officer  Martin Oduor-Otieno  told reporters today in
the capital, Nairobi.  
 United Bank for Africa Plc  (UBA NL), a Nigerian lender,
rose the most in more than two weeks, advancing 20 kobo, or 2
percent, to 10.2 naira. Net income totaled 4.85 billion naira
($32.2 million) in the six months through June, compared with a
loss of 3.94 million naira a year earlier, the Lagos-based bank
said in a statement to the Nigerian Stock Exchange today.  
